00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:18.540
[Guest]: So this is what Gary Becker tried to figure out.

00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:22.540
[Guest]: The way Gary Becker came to this insight was actually quite interesting.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:27.540
[Guest]: He was in a doctoral dissertation committee for an economics student at Columbia.

00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:33.540
[Guest]: And he was driving around the block of the university trying to find parking, which can be quite difficult in New York.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:38.540
[Guest]: And he was running terribly late, so he did some quick calculations in his head.

00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:49.540
[Guest]: He compared the cost of actually putting his car in a private parking garage, which can be quite expensive in New York, versus the penalty of parking illegally.

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:57.540
[Guest]: Except he didn't just calculate the penalty of parking illegally, but the expectation of what he would actually have to pay,

00:05:57.540 --> 00:06:02.540
[Guest]: which is the penalty of parking illegally times the probability of getting caught.

00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:09.540
[Guest]: He thought that getting caught in the next hour or so for illegal parking was a very low probability event.

00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:17.540
[Guest]: And even though parking fines can run high in New York, he thought it would still end up being cheaper than putting the car in a private garage.

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:22.540
[Guest]: So he just parked illegally and ran into the doctoral dissertation defense.

00:06:22.540 --> 00:06:27.540
[Guest]: And the happy ending to the story is he actually did get a parking fine.

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:31.540
[Guest]: And the even happier ending is he actually started writing about this.

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:40.540
[Guest]: And he basically started a field called the economic analysis of crime, one of the many areas for which he won his Nobel Prize.

00:06:40.540 --> 00:06:43.540
[Guest]: Now, Gary Becker's example is fairly simple.

00:06:43.540 --> 00:06:51.540
[Guest]: We've all made some kind of an error in figuring out, you know, how we reach somewhere on time.

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:54.540
[Guest]: We've all faced the problem of not being able to find parking.

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:58.540
[Guest]: I'm sure we've all dodged a few parking fines.

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:04.540
[Guest]: But what Gary Becker was telling us was this is true even for the more serious crimes.

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:10.540
[Guest]: You basically look at what your expected cost of an illegal action will be.

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:19.540
[Guest]: And the expected cost is the actual penalty, which is usually jail time for serious crimes, times the probability of actually being convicted.

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:26.540
[Guest]: Right. So let's say the actual penalty for a particular crime is 10 years in jail.

00:07:26.540 --> 00:07:30.540
[Guest]: But the probability of getting convicted is only 10 percent.

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:36.540
[Guest]: So your expected cost or your expected punishment is actually only one year in jail.

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:45.540
[Guest]: If you can improve the conviction rates or the probability of getting convicted to, say, 40 percent, right,

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:51.540
[Guest]: immediately the expected cost of the punishment increases to four years in prison.

00:07:51.540 --> 00:08:02.540
[Guest]: So when you mentioned in your introduction that people are very trigger happy to toss garbage or litter on the streets of Mumbai, but they never do it in Singapore,

00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:11.540
[Guest]: that's because there's really virtually no cost for that action in Mumbai, whereas in Singapore you could potentially face a penalty.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:22.540
[Guest]: So you might be willing to litter at zero or very close to zero cost, but you're not willing to litter for, say, a $40 fine, the expected probability of a $40 fine.

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:24.540
[Guest]: And that's really what changes things.

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:36.540
[Guest]: So one way to correct criminal behavior, according to Gary Becker, is in one sense to impose appropriate punishments,

00:08:36.540 --> 00:08:43.540
[Guest]: but also you could fix that problem by the other part of the equation, which is improving the chances of getting caught.

00:08:43.540 --> 00:08:47.540
[Amit Varma]: Let me kind of summarize it. I mean, what you're saying makes a lot of sense.

00:08:47.540 --> 00:08:51.540
[Amit Varma]: In poker terms, for example, we often talk about the expected value of an action.

00:08:51.540 --> 00:09:00.540
[Amit Varma]: So just to go over the parking example, let's say Gary Becker is circling the block and he wants to park, and a private parking will cost him $100.

00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:05.540
[Amit Varma]: And the fine for illegal parking is $1,000, but he'll be caught only one in 20 times.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:16.540
[Amit Varma]: Now, because he'll be caught only one in 20 times, that means it's $1,000 divided by 20, which is $50, which is a lower cost to pay than the private parking, which is $100.

00:09:16.540 --> 00:09:25.540
[Amit Varma]: So in poker playing terms, you'd argue that the EV or the expected value of parking illegally is actually plus $50, and therefore he should park illegally.

00:09:25.540 --> 00:09:32.540
[Amit Varma]: Now, the point you're making is that in this example, there are two ways to make sure that he doesn't park illegally.

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:35.540
[Amit Varma]: One way is you increase the fine.

00:09:35.540 --> 00:09:49.540
[Amit Varma]: So if the fine is $10,000 instead of $1,000, then his expected cost, if he gets caught one in 20 times, is $500 instead of $50, which is much more than the $100 that a private parking would cost.

00:09:49.540 --> 00:10:02.540
[Amit Varma]: The other way is if you keep the fine the same, but he's caught, say, 30% of the time, then again, you know, instead of one in 20 times, and the cost goes up to $300, and that again is more expensive than the private parking.

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:11.540
[Amit Varma]: So the two ways you typically handle this is make the punishment more severe or make the probability for getting caught higher.

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:21.540
[Amit Varma]: And the thing that I should point out, which I know a lot of listeners that must come to their mind is that hey, they'll be thinking like no criminal actually calculates these costs per se.

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:36.540
