00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:15.540
[Guest]: And 94% of the perpetrators are known to the victim. Only 6% are completely unknown.

00:22:15.540 --> 00:22:26.540
[Guest]: And I'm not talking boyfriends. Right. I'm talking school teacher, grandparent, uncle, next door neighbor.

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:30.540
[Guest]: This is like the immediate close community. It's really shocking.

00:22:30.540 --> 00:22:35.540
[Amit Varma]: And that's where the power imbalance is the greatest. Because if you're a minor, you're the least powerful.

00:22:35.540 --> 00:22:42.540
[Amit Varma]: And if the person molesting you is or raping you is, you know, your school teacher or your uncle or whatever,

00:22:42.540 --> 00:22:47.540
[Amit Varma]: you know, they're in the position of power. It's opportunity meets power imbalance.

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:52.540
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I mean, it's a very dismal picture as far as serious sexual assaults and rapes are concerned.

00:22:52.540 --> 00:22:58.540
[Amit Varma]: Like you said that, you know, men can get away with impunity because A, the costs of reporting on women are very high,

00:22:58.540 --> 00:23:02.540
[Amit Varma]: both socially and in terms of what the legal system will put them through,

00:23:02.540 --> 00:23:06.540
[Amit Varma]: which women have described as a second rape in some cases.

00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:11.540
[Amit Varma]: Two, the conviction rates are so low, even after the extremely low reporting rate,

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:14.540
[Amit Varma]: that they might as well not exist in this situation perpetuates itself.

00:23:14.540 --> 00:23:19.540
[Amit Varma]: In the kind of smaller context of what your piece was about and of Me Too,

00:23:19.540 --> 00:23:24.540
[Amit Varma]: which is not about this deeper, larger problem, which is, you know, makes both of us despair.

00:23:24.540 --> 00:23:28.540
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, we'll come back to it later. But just in the context of Me Too,

00:23:28.540 --> 00:23:33.540
[Amit Varma]: it seems that there has been a shift or maybe I'm mistaken, and it's just in elite circles like ours,

00:23:33.540 --> 00:23:39.540
[Amit Varma]: where women are finding validation in the fact that other women are speaking up.

00:23:39.540 --> 00:23:42.540
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, they are more likely to speak up themselves.

00:23:42.540 --> 00:23:48.540
[Amit Varma]: And that has caused a change in the amount of social sanction that a harasser has to then face.

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:55.540
[Amit Varma]: And this changes the incentives more towards, you know, men actually being punished for their behavior.

00:23:55.540 --> 00:23:58.540
[Guest]: Yeah, so let me break that up into little bits.

00:23:58.540 --> 00:24:05.540
[Guest]: So the first part about solidarity with other women and the victims, I can't tell you,

00:24:05.540 --> 00:24:10.540
[Guest]: at least in my experience as a woman, I have no experience in any other gender,

00:24:10.540 --> 00:24:15.540
[Guest]: just how incredibly important that is. So I went to an all girls school.

00:24:15.540 --> 00:24:19.540
[Guest]: My closest friends from my childhood were mostly women.

00:24:19.540 --> 00:24:22.540
[Guest]: And there's like this deep sisterhood between all of us.

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:26.540
[Guest]: Of my six or seven first cousins, there's only one male first cousins.

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:34.540
[Guest]: All the others are sisters. I'm sort of surrounded by this sort of like female solidarity.

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:37.540
[Guest]: But it's not just about the immediate family.

00:24:37.540 --> 00:24:41.540
[Guest]: You've obviously never traveled in an all women's compartment.

00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:43.540
[Guest]: So let me just explain the dynamics of that.

00:24:43.540 --> 00:24:50.540
[Guest]: So if you travel in the Bombay local train or the Delhi metro, there is one or two compartments,

00:24:50.540 --> 00:24:52.540
[Guest]: which is just reserved for women. Right.

00:24:52.540 --> 00:24:57.540
[Guest]: And you should see the kind of sisterhood when you enter a compartment like that,

00:24:57.540 --> 00:25:01.540
[Guest]: especially the Delhi metro. All the compartments are connected. They're seamless.

00:25:01.540 --> 00:25:05.540
[Guest]: They'll always be like some of these roadside romeo types who will be standing at the edge,

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:08.540
[Guest]: nearing into the women's compartment.

00:25:08.540 --> 00:25:12.540
[Guest]: And they will try and inch and make their way into the women's compartment.

00:25:12.540 --> 00:25:18.540
[Guest]: And some auntie or young lady will literally take out her chappal.

00:25:18.540 --> 00:25:22.540
[Guest]: Right. And she will fling her shoe at him or like sort of point her shoe at him

00:25:22.540 --> 00:25:25.540
[Guest]: and ask him to get out of the lady's compartment.

00:25:25.540 --> 00:25:30.540
[Guest]: It's really difficult to do that alone if you're alone in a parking lot or something

00:25:30.540 --> 00:25:33.540
[Guest]: with a potential sexual predator.

00:25:33.540 --> 00:25:37.540
[Guest]: There is so much solidarity when you are 200 women standing in a compartment.

00:25:37.540 --> 00:25:41.540
[Guest]: And the moment you do that, you're the brave person to take that action.

00:25:41.540 --> 00:25:45.540
[Guest]: 20 women will say, oh, thank you, auntie. Thank you, didi. Thank you for doing that.

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:51.540
[Guest]: That guy made me so uncomfortable. So I think, I mean, society in general

00:25:51.540 --> 00:25:54.540
[Guest]: underestimates the value of this kind of solidarity.

00:25:54.540 --> 00:25:59.540
[Guest]: And men just simply don't understand it because I've been having this conversation

00:25:59.540 --> 00:26:04.540
[Guest]: with the men in my life. And we're slowly realizing that men and women

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:11.540
[Guest]: inhabit quite different social worlds, even when we're in the exact same physical space.

00:26:11.540 --> 00:26:18.540
[Guest]: Right. For women, one of the biggest sort of deterrence of speaking up is

00:26:18.540 --> 00:26:24.540
[Guest]: what if I speak up and either they don't believe me or they blame me.

00:26:24.540 --> 00:26:30.540
[Guest]: Right. Which is much worse than just not speaking up at all, because then you only

00:26:30.540 --> 00:26:35.540
[Guest]: have to live with trauma one, which is the trauma of the original sexual assault.

00:26:35.540 --> 00:26:39.540
[Guest]: Right. Trauma two, trauma three, all of those things don't come up.

00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:45.540
[Guest]: I've been looking at the Twitter comments on the pages of all these incredibly brave women

00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:49.540
[Guest]: who've spoken up in the MeToo movement. And it's so shocking.

00:26:49.540 --> 00:26:52.540
[Guest]: So many times people are like, but why were you working late?

00:26:52.540 --> 00:26:58.540
[Guest]: Why did you go alone to the hotel room? Is that an appropriate question to ask?

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:03.540
[Guest]: Right. It shouldn't matter. Why can't I work late? Right.

00:27:03.540 --> 00:27:09.540
[Guest]: If I get invited to a hotel lobby or a hotel room, why is it such a terrible expectation

00:27:09.540 --> 00:27:15.540
[Guest]: that I walk out, you know, just untouched or unmolested?

00:27:15.540 --> 00:27:18.540
[Guest]: So we've sort of turned it on the head so much.

00:27:18.540 --> 00:27:23.540
[Guest]: So there's slut shaming, there is victim shaming. And now there's a new kind of shaming.

00:27:23.540 --> 00:27:29.540
[Guest]: I call it like the prudence shaming. Right. This is all imprudent behavior.

00:27:29.540 --> 00:27:33.540
[Guest]: Watching a movie late at night is not prudent. Right.

00:27:33.540 --> 00:27:38.540
[Guest]: Going anywhere where you don't have seven other close people with you is imprudent.

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:43.540
[Guest]: If you always knew that the editor in your office was a Rangeeli Mizaj ki,

00:27:43.540 --> 00:27:46.540
[Guest]: then why did you go so close to him? That was imprudent.

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:49.540
[Guest]: It's your fault. You should have known. Right.

00:27:49.540 --> 00:27:55.540
[Guest]: This is just such an extraordinarily large problem that we face on a daily basis.

00:27:55.540 --> 00:28:00.540
[Guest]: And it's everywhere. It's our parents. It's our teachers. Right.

00:28:00.540 --> 00:28:03.540
[Guest]: You go out somewhere and you say that, you know,

00:28:03.540 --> 00:28:07.540
[Guest]: I was molested in a bus or I was like groped or leered at. And people are like, where's your dupatta?

00:28:07.540 --> 00:28:10.540
[Guest]: That's the first thing they ask you as if it's not a dupatta,

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:14.540
[Guest]: but like a gun which would have protected you against some kind of molestation. Right.

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:18.540
[Guest]: So they always and when I say they, I don't just mean men.

00:28:18.540 --> 00:28:22.540
[Guest]: I mean, men and women and of every generation.

00:28:22.540 --> 00:28:27.540
[Guest]: It's always turned on its head and the women are asked, why did you put yourself in this situation?

00:28:27.540 --> 00:28:30.540
[Guest]: And let me explain what the situation is. The situation is every situation.

00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:35.540
[Guest]: Why did you go to work? Why did you travel in public transport? Right.

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:37.540
[Guest]: Why did you stay 20 minutes extra after?

00:28:37.540 --> 00:28:44.540
[Guest]: Why were you in a situation where you were alone in an elevator or a room or a conference room with another person who happens to be a man?

00:28:44.540 --> 00:28:48.540
[Guest]: Every situation is the fault of the victim.

00:28:48.540 --> 00:28:53.540
[Guest]: So what ends up happening for women is this additional pressure of prudence.

00:28:53.540 --> 00:28:58.540
[Guest]: And the standard for this prudent behavior keeps changing every day. Right.

00:28:58.540 --> 00:29:05.540
[Guest]: Earlier, it was just don't go to a very scary, dark place alone late at night.

00:29:05.540 --> 00:29:09.540
[Guest]: Something that's unfamiliar, like a jungle or something.

00:29:09.540 --> 00:29:12.540
[Guest]: And now I'll tell you what happened to me last time.

00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:20.540
[Guest]: I was coming back on the Noida toll road and my driver lowered the window to pay the toll.

00:29:20.540 --> 00:29:24.540
[Guest]: And there was some problem over the amount of change calculated.

00:29:24.540 --> 00:29:33.540
[Guest]: OK, so after about two minutes of them arguing with each other, I lowered my window and the driver just freaked out.

00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:38.540
[Guest]: Like he just freaked out, turned around and said, Bailey, close the window.

00:29:38.540 --> 00:29:43.540
[Guest]: And you're asking what happened. And he's like, you don't know who's there with him next to him in the toll booth.

00:29:43.540 --> 00:29:49.540
[Guest]: We've just stopped in the middle of the road late in the evening and anyone could enter the car or molest you through the window.

00:29:49.540 --> 00:29:54.540
[Guest]: Right. So now lowering your window at a signal is imprudent behavior.

00:29:54.540 --> 00:30:01.540
[Guest]: Everything is imprudent behavior. So in this kind of world, there's the additional burden of the moment a victim speaks up.

00:30:01.540 --> 00:30:07.540
[Guest]: You're so worried that 20 people are going to blame you for doing something that is perfectly ordinary had nothing happened.

00:30:07.540 --> 00:30:18.540
[Guest]: And it's perfectly ordinary for a man, but is really ridiculously poor judgment on your part for engaging in that because you got molested.

00:30:18.540 --> 00:30:22.540
[Guest]: And therefore it must be your fault. So sorry for the long winded answer.

00:30:22.540 --> 00:30:27.540
[Amit Varma]: But this social solidarity part is so important in the MeToo movement.

00:30:27.540 --> 00:30:35.540
[Amit Varma]: So I have like two speculations here. And one is that perhaps, you know, what you point out about the solidarity being so important to women.

00:30:35.540 --> 00:30:44.540
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, my previous guest in the MeToo episode that I did a couple of weeks ago, Nikita Saxena was making the same point about how all the women are checking in with each other and so on.

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:53.540
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that the reason that that solidarity may be such a big deal with women while men don't really care about it is that women just need it more.

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:58.540
[Amit Varma]: Because men don't carry the burden of their maleness around everywhere.

00:30:58.540 --> 00:31:05.540
[Amit Varma]: While, you know, women in the patriarchal system, as you correctly say, it's a factor in every single thing that you do.

00:31:05.540 --> 00:31:11.540
