00:38:49.540 --> 00:38:56.540
[Guest]: So the cost for third parties to participate and provide solidarity, provide publicity have reduced.

00:38:56.540 --> 00:39:03.540
[Guest]: Now, because the first three costs have reduced for the victims and the third party or impartial spectators,

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:08.540
[Guest]: now the costs have increased for the perpetrators. Right.

00:39:08.540 --> 00:39:15.540
[Guest]: Because immediately earlier, when a woman would tell a story, either people around her would shush her and tell her not to tell anybody.

00:39:15.540 --> 00:39:22.540
[Guest]: Right. Or even if she made an effort to reach out and tell a few people, it's a few people.

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:28.540
[Guest]: Now you are being shamed on social media, being retweeted thousands of times.

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:31.540
[Guest]: It gets picked up by mainstream press. Right.

00:39:31.540 --> 00:39:36.540
[Guest]: People at your workplace and your families and your children are going to hear about it.

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:40.540
[Guest]: So suddenly the costs of being a sexual perpetrator are mounting.

00:39:40.540 --> 00:39:44.540
[Guest]: And there's the additional aspect of social trust. Right.

00:39:44.540 --> 00:39:50.540
[Guest]: I mean, there's still a lot of victim blaming and things like that and not believing victims first person accounts.

00:39:50.540 --> 00:39:56.540
[Guest]: But we found that usually some of the very bogus claims have been immediately rejected. Right.

00:39:56.540 --> 00:40:05.540
[Guest]: We know of one or two instances like this where an account was created yesterday and they made like a random allegation against someone and no one really believed it and blew it up.

00:40:05.540 --> 00:40:10.540
[Guest]: Whereas the people who we always knew were sexual predators as a society.

00:40:10.540 --> 00:40:14.540
[Guest]: There are multiple accounts. People now genuinely believe them.

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:22.540
[Guest]: Mainstream media is actually using social media accounts and publishing it in newspapers. Right.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:27.540
[Guest]: As if 100 people retweeting is the fact check for this particular case.

00:40:27.540 --> 00:40:34.540
[Guest]: So those are some really wonderful things. And this kind of social exposure will definitely impose greater costs.

00:40:34.540 --> 00:40:39.540
[Guest]: The other part of the Internet is it doesn't forget. So the costs are very long term.

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:48.540
[Guest]: Anytime anyone Googles M.J. Akbar's name or Sajid Khan's name from now until eternity, this stuff is going to pop up.

00:40:48.540 --> 00:40:52.540
[Guest]: So you can't it's not as fickle as memory of regular people in society.

00:40:52.540 --> 00:40:56.540
[Amit Varma]: And all of this, in fact, is illustrated by what just happened to M.J. Akbar.

00:40:56.540 --> 00:41:02.540
[Amit Varma]: I should point out that we are recording this on October 18th and it'll probably the episode will broadcast 10 days from now.

00:41:02.540 --> 00:41:06.540
[Amit Varma]: But as of 18th, you know, yesterday, M.J. Akbar resigned.

00:41:06.540 --> 00:41:19.540
[Amit Varma]: And I think initially he refused to resign and he filed a criminal defamation case against Priya Ramani because he must have made the assumption that, oh, it's just one person and I will intimidate her and there'll be a chilling effect.

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:22.540
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there were a bunch of people at the time, but he thought that's where it ends.

00:41:22.540 --> 00:41:32.540
[Amit Varma]: But instead, he fell for what is called the Barbara Streisand effect, that if you try to stop something from happening on social media, you only end up amplifying it.

00:41:32.540 --> 00:41:44.540
[Amit Varma]: And what basically happened was that the moment he filed the case on Priya, a whole bunch of other women came forward and said, look, either the same thing happened to them or they were witnesses to it and they were going to stand by her side.

00:41:44.540 --> 00:41:53.540
[Amit Varma]: And this included some really senior formidable women, as Priya herself is, it included people like Minal Baghel and Tushita Patel and you don't mess with those people.

00:41:53.540 --> 00:41:57.540
[Amit Varma]: And Akbar eventually got the memo and he had to step down.

00:41:57.540 --> 00:42:00.540
[Amit Varma]: And at the time of recording, we don't know what will happen to the case.

00:42:00.540 --> 00:42:12.540
[Amit Varma]: But what again happened there was that after the first person had the courage to put her story forward, there were all these other women who realized that, yes, this is a pattern and yes, I am validated.

00:42:12.540 --> 00:42:15.540
[Amit Varma]: It's not just me and I can also speak up now.

00:42:15.540 --> 00:42:20.540
[Amit Varma]: And that led to a cascade of people speaking up, which made it something unstoppable.

00:42:20.540 --> 00:42:30.540
[Amit Varma]: And just seeing this pattern of behavior being described by multiple credible women was almost more powerful than any kind of evidence you would need.

00:42:30.540 --> 00:42:35.540
[Amit Varma]: You know, it becomes obvious to anyone who's reading it that yes, this stuff has happened.

00:42:35.540 --> 00:42:43.540
[Amit Varma]: And not only are women far more likelier to speak up when they see others speaking up, but earlier your social sanction was relatively low.

00:42:43.540 --> 00:42:54.540
[Amit Varma]: But what we've seen now in this MeToo movement, which gives me so much hope, is that you've had a minister stepping down, you've had a variety of people getting sacked from where they worked.

00:42:54.540 --> 00:43:02.540
[Amit Varma]: In most cases, before the inquiry against them was even complete, before the due process even played out, these guys just got sacked.

00:43:02.540 --> 00:43:06.540
[Amit Varma]: And to me, it seems as if that changes the incentives completely.

00:43:06.540 --> 00:43:09.540
[Guest]: Well, it does and it doesn't.

00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:10.540
[Guest]: And I'll tell you in what context.

00:43:10.540 --> 00:43:15.540
[Guest]: So it changes the incentives for certain kinds of perpetrators and certain kinds of victims.

00:43:15.540 --> 00:43:19.540
[Guest]: So it has definitely changed the game for serial perpetrators.

00:43:19.540 --> 00:43:20.540
[Guest]: Right.

00:43:20.540 --> 00:43:37.540
[Guest]: So anyone who like MJ Appar or Sajid Khan, like people who just have a reputation for notoriously preying on women one after the other, because, you know, all the credibility that is coming to these stories is the credibility of a large number of women coming together.

00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:38.540
[Guest]: Right.

00:43:38.540 --> 00:43:44.540
[Guest]: So one problem is social media is still on a great place to sift out the singular allegation.

00:43:44.540 --> 00:43:52.540
[Guest]: Right. That single crime because the opportunity presented itself or someone was inebriated or something like that.

00:43:52.540 --> 00:44:01.540
[Guest]: And social media is not a very good place to sort that out because what ends happening on social media is, oh, this is a he said, she said case.

00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:09.540
[Guest]: OK, then. And the only belief cases where it's he said and then she said, she said, she said, she said, she said, she said, she said.

00:44:09.540 --> 00:44:12.540
[Guest]: So this is one particular kind of problem.

00:44:12.540 --> 00:44:17.540
[Guest]: So I agree with you that for the worst offenders, things have definitely changed.

00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:25.540
[Guest]: The second is there are not not every victim is in a position that Priya is in.

00:44:25.540 --> 00:44:30.540
[Guest]: Right. Priya is an incredibly brave woman with.

00:44:30.540 --> 00:44:35.540
[Guest]: And I read her husband's account. It's an incredibly supportive husband and family.

00:44:35.540 --> 00:44:44.540
[Guest]: Quite clearly, she has a powering reputation within among journalists and generally within the media circles.

00:44:44.540 --> 00:44:51.540
[Guest]: And she has a particular kind of credibility that has been earned over a few decades and that takes time to earn.

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:59.540
[Guest]: Right. When you talk about girls just starting out, you know, the most vulnerable victims, we must remember this happened to Priya 25 years ago.

00:44:59.540 --> 00:45:04.540
[Guest]: And at that time, no one would have believed the Priya who was 25 years younger.

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:18.540
[Guest]: And even today, there are so many people who are just at the start of their career and people simply don't believe them because they don't bring that kind of network credibility that has been earned over a long period of time.

00:45:18.540 --> 00:45:26.540
[Guest]: And if social credibility is the only way we're going to sift through sexual assault cases, it's unfortunately not a very good thing.

00:45:26.540 --> 00:45:34.540
[Amit Varma]: No, but Shruti, for example, before we started recording, I jokingly mentioned to you this place called Happy Creative Agencies or something like that.

00:45:34.540 --> 00:45:38.540
[Amit Varma]: I think it's an arm of Dentsu where four senior guys have got sacked.

00:45:38.540 --> 00:45:46.540
[Amit Varma]: And if I'm not mistaken, most of the complaints were from young people about harassment who don't have, who are like the Priya Ramani of 25 years ago would have been.

00:45:46.540 --> 00:45:49.540
[Guest]: They were also not taking on an M.J. Akbar. That's true.

00:45:49.540 --> 00:45:58.540
[Guest]: That's the part I want to explain. Right. So Priya Ramani is a towering presence who can take on a minister in the union government.

00:45:58.540 --> 00:46:02.540
[Guest]: Now, let's scale that down smaller. What about a woman?

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:10.540
[Guest]: What about someone who's a district collector, upper caste male in a village and is preying on lower caste women?

00:46:10.540 --> 00:46:14.540
[Guest]: How is this going to play out? These women have mobile phones now.

00:46:14.540 --> 00:46:25.540
[Guest]: The literacy is improving. And because literacy is improving, there is greater reporting of sexual assault cases in India because they have social media and access to mobile phones and they watch news.

00:46:25.540 --> 00:46:32.540
[Guest]: They know what's going on in the MeToo movement. But how are they going to use the MeToo movement to expose this guy?

00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:37.540
[Guest]: It's not so clear to me. By the way, again, I don't want to delegitimize the MeToo movement.

00:46:37.540 --> 00:46:46.540
[Guest]: I just want to point out that this is not an equal platform for all types of people and it is not an equal platform for all types of offenses.

00:46:46.540 --> 00:46:53.540
[Guest]: It is a platform where the people who have greatest media exposure are going to have the biggest fall. Right.

00:46:53.540 --> 00:47:01.540
[Guest]: So those sexual predators who are at the highest levels of society and have been hiding in plain sight will have the greatest fall.

00:47:01.540 --> 00:47:10.540
[Guest]: But there are a lot of sexual predators who are in a position of power that the English speaking press is not going to report on them or even the vernacular press is not going to report on them

00:47:10.540 --> 00:47:15.540
[Guest]: because the power structure in that particular society is quite complicated. Right.

00:47:15.540 --> 00:47:18.540
[Guest]: And the victims in that society, people will simply not believe.

00:47:18.540 --> 00:47:22.540
[Guest]: This is another problem with the way the police stations are structured.

00:47:22.540 --> 00:47:28.540
[Guest]: Police stations have very few lower caste people and virtually no lower caste women working there.

00:47:28.540 --> 00:47:35.540
[Guest]: And most victims of sexual assault in rural areas are Dalit women. Right.

00:47:35.540 --> 00:47:45.540
[Guest]: So now go back to our conversation about solidarity, support, believability, their credibility in a particular reporting environment.

00:47:45.540 --> 00:47:57.540
[Guest]: Those women have none of these wonderful benefits coming to them, even though they want to be part of the social media MeToo movement.

00:47:57.540 --> 00:48:03.540
[Guest]: And it's not so clear to me that the benefits extend to them, at least not in the same equal way.

00:48:03.540 --> 00:48:10.540
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, before we move on to that subject and move away from the MeToo movement, you know, when it comes to the MeToo movement,

00:48:10.540 --> 00:48:16.540
[Amit Varma]: we're probably talking past each other and saying the same thing because I'm not saying that it's a panacea and it's going to solve everything.

00:48:16.540 --> 00:48:25.540
[Amit Varma]: I just think that it shifts the probability slightly. It's not that every woman is going to report crimes against her, but it makes it slightly more likely.

00:48:25.540 --> 00:48:32.540
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, this is much more true in elite circles and circles where women don't have access to social media and technology and so on.

00:48:32.540 --> 00:48:39.540
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, to go back to even the earlier point where you made the point that it's something where we'll see the effect for serial predators

00:48:39.540 --> 00:48:46.540
[Amit Varma]: who have a pattern of behavior and we won't see it so much for what some people call the bad date gone wrong kind of situation.

00:48:46.540 --> 00:48:53.540
[Amit Varma]: I disagree there again, because what happens in some of those smaller cases where men don't recognize boundaries is that there is a tendency

00:48:53.540 --> 00:49:02.540
[Amit Varma]: among many men when they are dating to ignore a woman's discomfort where she doesn't have to say no, but she's uncomfortable,

00:49:02.540 --> 00:49:09.540
[Amit Varma]: but they will ignore it as, for example, in the Aziz Ansari case, because they just want to get away with as much as they can.

00:49:09.540 --> 00:49:18.540
[Amit Varma]: And I think the incentives now shift towards them being more cognizant of a woman's discomfort, even when she doesn't overtly say no.

00:49:18.540 --> 00:49:25.540
[Guest]: And I think that's kind of a good thing. I agree, but I will put in a couple of caveats.

00:49:25.540 --> 00:49:32.540
[Guest]: When I talk to women, especially those who've been talking about, you know, bad experiences.

00:49:32.540 --> 00:49:41.540
[Guest]: When you ask them why you didn't report it before, because most of the women I know are in, you know, circumstances of very high levels of privilege.

00:49:41.540 --> 00:49:49.540
[Guest]: The first thing they say is, I didn't want to hurt my parents. It would have broken my dad's heart. Right.

00:49:49.540 --> 00:49:57.540
[Guest]: So many victims of sexual assault still want to remain anonymous, even within the MeToo movement, not because they are lying, you know,

00:49:57.540 --> 00:50:04.540
[Guest]: in part because they'll be socially shamed. But the one group that they don't want finding out about this incident is their parents,

00:50:04.540 --> 00:50:10.540
[Guest]: because it would kill their parents to find out that their child had been through this trauma. Right.

00:50:10.540 --> 00:50:15.540
[Guest]: So that's the caveat I want to add. I agree that it has shifted incentives.

00:50:15.540 --> 00:50:21.540
[Guest]: I agree that now men in positions of power have to sit up and take notice.

00:50:21.540 --> 00:50:27.540
[Guest]: I agree that especially among the men you and I know, right, we have a lot of friends in common.

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:31.540
[Guest]: There's an ongoing conversation about, hey, have I been behaving appropriately?

00:50:31.540 --> 00:50:39.540
[Guest]: Did I make anyone uncomfortable? Are the jokes I'm making truly funny or are they sexist and making the women around me uncomfortable?

00:50:39.540 --> 00:50:45.540
[Guest]: So I agree with you. There's definitely a recognition of that. But the society we in it has not changed.

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:54.540
[Guest]: And a lot of the social pressures of the relationships between parents and their children or the relationship between the most.

00:50:54.540 --> 00:50:59.540
[Guest]: There's one more little thing I want to add. Most women don't report sexual assault,

00:50:59.540 --> 00:51:05.540
[Guest]: especially in privileged circumstances, also because the moment we do it, that's all we'll ever be known for.

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:14.540
[Guest]: And that's a genuine fear. Right. I want to be known as an economist working in this field and having published that paper.

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:24.540
[Guest]: I don't want the first Google article about me always to be about how I complained about some sexual predator in a particular circumstance.

00:51:24.540 --> 00:51:31.540
[Guest]: And it always becomes about that. So just like the male sexual predators, if we Google them,

00:51:31.540 --> 00:51:38.540
[Guest]: we're always going to know that, oh, this guy did something shady in the past. The same is true for the victim also.

00:51:38.540 --> 00:51:44.540
[Guest]: Right. The same thing. Now, every time you Google any one of these courageous women's names,

00:51:44.540 --> 00:51:48.540
[Guest]: I don't think it's their wonderful journalism that's going to pop up in the top hits.

00:51:48.540 --> 00:51:55.540
[Guest]: It's going to be this particular instance of them against M.J. Akbar or them against Sajid Khan or something else.

00:51:55.540 --> 00:52:03.540
[Guest]: So they will be known for a very singular event that they may not want to be reminded of and they frankly don't want to be known for that.

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:08.540
[Guest]: So I want to add these caveats, not because I think men aren't changing,

00:52:08.540 --> 00:52:16.540
[Guest]: but just because social media reduces particular kinds of costs doesn't mean that we are now radically in a different world.

00:52:16.540 --> 00:52:24.540
[Guest]: I know that's not what you're saying, but I just want to add that caveat because I think we're all caught up in a wonderful cultural moment.

00:52:24.540 --> 00:52:28.540
[Guest]: And I think it's useful to understand the limitations of that cultural moment.

00:52:28.540 --> 00:52:31.540
[Amit Varma]: No, that's a great point. But just to clarify what I was saying,

00:52:31.540 --> 00:52:38.540
[Amit Varma]: I absolutely don't want to minimize all the social pressures and costs that a woman bears.

00:52:38.540 --> 00:52:45.540
[Amit Varma]: The only point I'm making is that earlier, if a woman, especially in elite circles, was, say, 1% likely to report something,

00:52:45.540 --> 00:52:51.540
[Amit Varma]: that 1% might have gone up to 1.5%, which is still incredibly low because of the huge amount of pressures.

00:52:51.540 --> 00:52:55.540
[Amit Varma]: And it's not 100%, but it's still 50% more than what it was before.

00:52:55.540 --> 00:53:05.540
[Guest]: Absolutely. And the reporting gets magnified now, right? 1.5% will get retweeted a thousand times and people will take notice and they'll say things like,

00:53:05.540 --> 00:53:11.540
[Guest]: I can't believe that guy did that. I can't believe we have a sexual predator hiding in plain sight.

00:53:11.540 --> 00:53:17.540
[Guest]: I can't believe I went to that party with him. Right. I know so many people right now who are having that moment.

00:53:17.540 --> 00:53:25.540
[Guest]: I can't believe I invited this person to my home or spend time with his family or this one I've played with his children.

00:53:25.540 --> 00:53:31.540
[Guest]: This is a moment that is really catching up with all of us. It definitely makes us sit up and take notice.

00:53:31.540 --> 00:53:36.540
[Guest]: And I think the longer term the consequences are, the better it is. Right.

00:53:36.540 --> 00:53:44.540
[Guest]: One fear I have is, which is now reducing with each passing day, the fear I had two weeks ago was this will all blow over.

00:53:44.540 --> 00:53:50.540
[Guest]: Why? Because the new cycle is so fickle. Right. Something comes up today. We make a big deal about it.

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:54.540
[Guest]: And two weeks later, we have gone back to making Rahul Gandhi jokes or something like that.

00:53:54.540 --> 00:53:59.540
[Guest]: Like everyone just forgets. But the longer term the consequences are, the better.

00:53:59.540 --> 00:54:12.540
[Guest]: So I saw this wonderful, I think it was a press release or something by 10 or 12 female directors who said they will not work with any of the proven sexual offenders.

00:54:12.540 --> 00:54:21.540
[Guest]: Right. That's a really clean stand. It doesn't matter whether you're a hairdresser or whether you're a director or an actor or a casting agent.

00:54:21.540 --> 00:54:29.540
[Guest]: We are simply not going to work with you. And that is the kind of long term and the really high cost economic consequence we need.

00:54:29.540 --> 00:54:35.540
[Guest]: We need these people to be sacked. We need their awards and invitations to be rescinded. Right.

00:54:35.540 --> 00:54:46.540
[Guest]: We need some very long term effects. I would love if publishers start dropping the book deals of all the people who have been accused who happen to be writers.

00:54:46.540 --> 00:54:54.540
[Guest]: Right. Bollywood is already dropping. I think two directors have been dropped from projects and their names have been removed and things like that.

00:54:54.540 --> 00:55:03.540
[Guest]: That's the signal we need to send. Not only that we believe the women, but that we will not just do like a fake inquiry internally.

00:55:03.540 --> 00:55:07.540
[Guest]: There are some real long term economic costs associated with this act.

00:55:07.540 --> 00:55:15.540
[Amit Varma]: There definitely are. For example, the Mami Film Festival, which would have started by the time you listen to this episode, but is now a week away and which I'm very excited about,

00:55:15.540 --> 00:55:24.540
[Amit Varma]: has dropped films by Rajat Kapoor and All India Bakchod after what happened. And, you know, just going back to that press release by those 12 women directors or whatever,

00:55:24.540 --> 00:55:32.540
[Amit Varma]: I thought it was great, but I thought, where are the 12 male directors saying the same thing? That would also, this is not a fight that women alone have to fight.

00:55:32.540 --> 00:55:44.540
[Guest]: No, actually, it's the opposite. It's the fight where women need men the most, because no matter what we say about how empowered we are and how wonderful the Mito movement is,

00:55:44.540 --> 00:55:55.540
[Guest]: in most industries, the men occupy the highest sort of areas or levels of power and economic power and social status.

00:55:55.540 --> 00:56:02.540
[Guest]: And until the men just come out and unilaterally call this out and distance themselves, it's not going to work.

00:56:02.540 --> 00:56:10.540
[Guest]: Because what will happen is the female directors won't work with these people, but they're only 12 versus the 300 male directors.

00:56:10.540 --> 00:56:21.540
[Guest]: Exactly. Right. So these men may, the sexual predators may still find employment in these bro dude clubs and green rooms where it's okay to have behaved badly.

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:29.540
[Guest]: So I completely agree with you. It's not just a women's movement. And frankly, the women need the men more than ever before,

00:56:29.540 --> 00:56:37.540
[Guest]: because so many of the decisions are taken by men and we need men to take a very clean stance on this,

00:56:37.540 --> 00:56:45.540
[Guest]: even when it's their closest friends and family members and co-workers and impose some kind of distance.

00:56:45.540 --> 00:56:52.540
[Amit Varma]: They should be social pariahs. Absolutely. I couldn't agree more. And, you know, we saw some of it. I mean, definitely the Mito movement has ended careers,

00:56:52.540 --> 00:56:59.540
[Amit Varma]: but again, has ended careers of some elite men in some context where women found the courage and the means to complain.

00:56:59.540 --> 00:57:08.540
[Amit Varma]: But like you said, it's not widespread enough. So shifting from Mito for the moment to just the wider criminal justice system and to the field of criminal economics,

00:57:08.540 --> 00:57:13.540
[Amit Varma]: for example, you've just pointed out, for example, let's not talk about English speaking elites anymore.

00:57:13.540 --> 00:57:18.540
[Amit Varma]: But if you just look at the rape reporting rates in the country or the conviction rates and so on,

00:57:18.540 --> 00:57:31.540
[Amit Varma]: what are the sort of insights that you'd get from the work of someone like Becker in terms of how can the criminal justice system be structured differently to make more of a positive impact?

00:57:31.540 --> 00:57:37.540
[Guest]: So, you know, this is now speaking only about the criminal justice system. There are three parts to it.

00:57:37.540 --> 00:57:47.540
[Guest]: One is the process of reporting. The second is the process of the actual trial. And the third is the result of the trial, which is the lack of conviction. Right.

00:57:47.540 --> 00:57:56.540
[Guest]: And I think on all three areas, India is extremely poor and has been getting worse. And Becker tells us how to fix this problem.

00:57:56.540 --> 00:58:03.540
[Guest]: So if you remember after the horrible Nirbhaya event, you know, there was this huge amount of public outrage.

00:58:03.540 --> 00:58:11.540
[Guest]: And how did we channelize that public outrage? All the people called for death penalty for gang rapists. Right.

00:58:11.540 --> 00:58:19.540
[Guest]: So that is only fixing one part of the Gary Becker equation, which is increase the punishment so high that it acts as a deterrent.

00:58:19.540 --> 00:58:26.540
[Guest]: But that's really hard to do in a state where there is very weak capacity and there are very low conviction.

00:58:26.540 --> 00:58:33.540
[Amit Varma]: And also, sorry for interrupting you, but would you agree that giving the death penalty for a rape is actually an incentive to murder?

00:58:33.540 --> 00:58:40.540
[Amit Varma]: Because then the criminal after committing a rape might think that, you know, might as well kill her because the penalty is the same and there's less chance of getting caught if I kill her.

00:58:40.540 --> 00:58:49.540
[Guest]: Yes. So that's one problem on the margin. Perpetrator is better off being a rapist plus murderer than simply a rapist because the punishment is the same.

00:58:49.540 --> 00:58:58.540
[Guest]: The second problem is the evidentiary burden is higher when we are giving someone the death penalty as it should be. Right.

00:58:58.540 --> 00:59:07.540
[Guest]: So because you absolutely don't want any false positives in a death penalty situation and that imposes an additional burden on the victim.

00:59:07.540 --> 00:59:14.540
[Guest]: So that is not what we want. What we want is to fix the other part of the Gary Becker equation,

00:59:14.540 --> 00:59:21.540
[Guest]: which is the probability of facing the cost or the probability of actually facing the legal punishment.

00:59:21.540 --> 00:59:30.540
[Guest]: So how do we improve that probability? We need to fix all three parts of the structure, which is the reporting structure, the trial structure, the conviction rate.

00:59:30.540 --> 00:59:35.540
[Guest]: And how do we fix that? The first part of it is just state capacity. Right.

00:59:35.540 --> 00:59:46.540
[Guest]: India has about, I think, 130 policemen for every 100,000 people. I've only lived in two countries, India and the United States.

00:59:46.540 --> 00:59:57.540
[Guest]: The United States has above 300. Right. So we have less than half of the number of policemen per 100,000 people than most other countries.

00:59:57.540 --> 01:00:05.540
[Guest]: So this is a really big problem because our police, they have a terrible reputation, but we must understand that they're also terribly constrained.

01:00:05.540 --> 01:00:10.540
[Guest]: They don't have budgets. They don't have resources. And frankly, they simply don't have the manpower.

01:00:10.540 --> 01:00:20.540
[Guest]: So our police force needs to increase like twofold or threefold if we want the reporting procedure to be simpler. Right.

01:00:20.540 --> 01:00:28.540
[Guest]: So that's the number one thing. The other part of making the reporting procedure more at ease is, again, the moment you have manpower,

01:00:28.540 --> 01:00:33.540
[Guest]: you can also have greater division of labor and specialization within each police station.

01:00:33.540 --> 01:00:47.540
[Guest]: And then maybe if you're not that severely resource constrained, you could have someone who just deals with cases of sexual assault and violence or cases where the victims are minors or something like that.

01:00:47.540 --> 01:00:55.540
[Guest]: Right. So that is the number one thing. And this just requires a very large amount of concerted political action.

01:00:55.540 --> 01:01:05.540
[Guest]: Right now, the political class is just not interested in expanding the resources given to the police and really empowering the police.

01:01:05.540 --> 01:01:15.540
[Guest]: Why? Because the more police is in their control and the lesser victims of crime have opportunities in the regular criminal justice system,

01:01:15.540 --> 01:01:19.540
[Guest]: the greater is the status and the power of the politicians. Right.

01:01:19.540 --> 01:01:23.540
[Guest]: Because now for everything you need to go to the politician instead of going to the police.

01:01:23.540 --> 01:01:30.540
[Guest]: So there's actually a very perverse incentive structure. The other part of it is most politicians are criminals.

01:01:30.540 --> 01:01:36.540
[Guest]: Right. In fact, if you read Milanvesh's wonderful book, he talks about the incentives for criminals becoming politicians,

01:01:36.540 --> 01:01:42.540
[Guest]: which means they really don't want a functional police and they want the police to be under their control.

01:01:42.540 --> 01:01:52.540
[Guest]: So the second part of making reporting easier is we need to remove police from state level control and make it municipal or local level.

01:01:52.540 --> 01:02:00.540
[Guest]: I think that would make a really big difference. So you can have a state level police force, but we also need like a local level police force,

01:02:00.540 --> 01:02:05.540
[Guest]: which can much better deal with local circumstances and also have local representation.

01:02:05.540 --> 01:02:12.540
[Guest]: Right. Women within the community may feel better if one of them is at the police station.

01:02:12.540 --> 01:02:19.540
[Guest]: And we see this a lot with the panchayati raj. Right. Those districts where women became the sarpanch,

01:02:19.540 --> 01:02:26.540
[Guest]: immediately the kinds of public goods tilted a little bit more in favor of the kinds of things that women need,

01:02:26.540 --> 01:02:31.540
[Guest]: such as water or like, you know, closeness to the closest water resource.

01:02:31.540 --> 01:02:40.540
[Guest]: So I think this is something that we need to think about structurally. The second part is the process of the trial and then the conviction rate.

01:02:40.540 --> 01:02:45.540
[Guest]: So the process of the trial, you know, India has these ridiculous pendency rates.

01:02:45.540 --> 01:02:56.540
[Guest]: They are worse than ever before. And one of the things that stops the victims from complaining is you need to relive this for the next eight years or 10 years.

01:02:56.540 --> 01:03:02.540
[Guest]: Right. And that's just at the district court level. And then if the perpetrator appeals, even if you get a conviction,

01:03:02.540 --> 01:03:06.540
[Guest]: you need to relive it again in the high court and again in the Supreme Court.

01:03:06.540 --> 01:03:13.540
[Guest]: So light is nowhere visible or it's at the end of a very, very long tunnel.

01:03:13.540 --> 01:03:22.540
[Guest]: And the second part of the problem is that your life is kind of put on hold just having to relive this problem over and over and over again.

01:03:22.540 --> 01:03:29.540
[Guest]: So the number one thing that victims of sexual assault need is you need a really quick and speedy trial.

01:03:29.540 --> 01:03:33.540
[Guest]: Right. And it's not that victims of other crimes don't need that.

01:03:33.540 --> 01:03:41.540
[Guest]: But I think it's really particularly imperative to provide that to victims of sexual assault.

01:03:41.540 --> 01:03:48.540
[Guest]: Right. Now, anytime these things come up, the government typically says we create these fast track courts,

01:03:48.540 --> 01:03:52.540
[Guest]: fast track so much that they don't follow proper procedure.

01:03:52.540 --> 01:03:57.540
[Guest]: So even when they do get a conviction, everything is reversed at the high court and the Supreme Court level.

01:03:57.540 --> 01:04:02.540
[Guest]: So we don't need fast track courts. We need our current courts to function better.

01:04:02.540 --> 01:04:10.540
[Guest]: Right. India has about a tenth of the judges that developed countries have.

01:04:10.540 --> 01:04:17.540
[Guest]: Right. So for 100000 people, I think India has about 12 judges or something like that.

01:04:17.540 --> 01:04:22.540
[Guest]: And where I live right now, the United States has about 115 or 120.

01:04:22.540 --> 01:04:32.540
[Guest]: So it's literally tenfold. Right. The aim may not be to reach American standards, but the aim could be to go reach halfway there.

01:04:32.540 --> 01:04:40.540
[Guest]: And so we need at least a fivefold increase in judges, if not a tenfold increase in judges.

01:04:40.540 --> 01:04:45.540
[Guest]: Right. Population has exploded. Reporting of crimes has increased over the years.

01:04:45.540 --> 01:04:52.540
[Guest]: But the number of judges and the court structure remains exactly the same.

01:04:52.540 --> 01:04:57.540
[Guest]: You had a couple of wonderful episodes on this where you guys talked about, you know,

01:04:57.540 --> 01:05:05.540
[Guest]: the actual structure of the courts and how the dates are assigned and how slow that process is and how that really needs to change in India.

01:05:05.540 --> 01:05:14.540
[Guest]: So those are the kinds of structural things that are going to reduce the cost for the victim and increase the cost for the perpetrator because it increases the chances of conviction.

01:05:14.540 --> 01:05:19.540
[Guest]: The third part of it is the actual conviction rate. And this depends on evidence. Right.

01:05:19.540 --> 01:05:27.540
[Guest]: In India, we don't have good method. So first of all, when and I'm going to talk about rape, not sexual assault.

01:05:27.540 --> 01:05:34.540
[Guest]: The moment there is a rape, we don't have a very good procedure for collecting evidence and creating a rape kit.

01:05:34.540 --> 01:05:42.540
[Guest]: Right. The moment victims actually go to the police station, first of all, so often they just sent home.

01:05:42.540 --> 01:05:47.540
[Guest]: Right. And they say, why don't you sleep on it and come back and report the crime in three days?

01:05:47.540 --> 01:05:53.540
[Guest]: Well, in three days, all the biological evidence is lost. Right.

01:05:53.540 --> 01:06:02.540
[Guest]: You need to record marks on the body or any kind of other DNA material that might have been left behind.

01:06:02.540 --> 01:06:10.540
[Guest]: Everything is washed away when you ask victims to wait three, four days or you send victims away when they're reporting a crime.

01:06:10.540 --> 01:06:16.540
[Guest]: All government hospitals are so overcrowded that are you going to save lives or are you going to make a rape kit?

01:06:16.540 --> 01:06:31.540
[Guest]: Right. So the conviction depends so much on evidence and our evidence collection and the way we handle it for a decade long trial is so poor that virtually there is no hope.

01:06:31.540 --> 01:06:35.540
[Guest]: There is no hope of getting a conviction unless you have 20 witnesses. Right.

01:06:35.540 --> 01:06:46.540
[Guest]: And most rapes don't happen with 20 witnesses. Unfortunately, many of them do in rural India where upper caste men just think they can strip and rape a Dalit woman in the middle of the village.

01:06:46.540 --> 01:06:51.540
[Guest]: But most rapes don't take place like that, which means most rapes you don't have photographic evidence.

01:06:51.540 --> 01:06:57.540
[Guest]: You don't have physical evidence. So the conviction rate is so strongly linked to that.

01:06:57.540 --> 01:07:03.540
[Guest]: And we need a bigger infrastructure of public goods and services which is dedicated to this.

01:07:03.540 --> 01:07:10.540
[Guest]: So absent these three things, I think it's very difficult to improve the probability of getting caught and convicted.

01:07:10.540 --> 01:07:16.540
[Guest]: That's a really big problem. The additional part associated with the cost on the perpetrator.

01:07:16.540 --> 01:07:22.540
[Guest]: Now, of course, a really long trial also hurts the perpetrator because it's a long trial. There's legal fees.

01:07:22.540 --> 01:07:26.540
[Guest]: But on the other hand, it also absorbs the perpetrator a little bit.

01:07:26.540 --> 01:07:33.540
[Guest]: Most men within the community or at the workplace are like, yeah, this is going to take 10 years. We can't suspend him for 10 years. Right.

01:07:33.540 --> 01:07:39.540
[Guest]: So the moment the perpetrator gets bail or something, they go back to work. And that is not the outcome that we want.

01:07:39.540 --> 01:07:47.540
[Guest]: So if there is a swift procedure, it both protects the perpetrators who are false positives and have been wrongly accused.

01:07:47.540 --> 01:07:51.540
[Guest]: But it also improves the chances of a social shaming system around it.

01:07:51.540 --> 01:07:57.540
[Guest]: Because, you know, there's media attention. We can focus on something for six months. We can't focus on something for 10 years.

01:07:57.540 --> 01:08:03.540
[Guest]: So even their social system, the workplace, their friends, their family, their alumni network.

01:08:03.540 --> 01:08:07.540
[Guest]: No one has the stamina to hold that in their mind for 10 years.

01:08:07.540 --> 01:08:13.540
[Guest]: And I think that's a really big problem of social cost being imposed on the perpetrators because of this.

01:08:13.540 --> 01:08:18.540
[Guest]: But that I would say is how we should interpret Gary Becker's big insight.

01:08:18.540 --> 01:08:22.540
[Guest]: We need to improve the probability of getting caught,

01:08:22.540 --> 01:08:31.540
[Guest]: which means addressing all these different various aspects of reporting the actual trial and the conviction rate and the appeals process,

01:08:31.540 --> 01:08:37.540
[Guest]: such that perpetrators think twice on the margin when they commit a crime.

01:08:37.540 --> 01:08:42.540
[Amit Varma]: So let me just sort of try and summarize a very depressing picture that you painted.

01:08:42.540 --> 01:08:50.540
[Amit Varma]: The first thing that you pointed out was that, look, you know, you kind of there are two things you typically address when you talk about the cost of a crime.

01:08:50.540 --> 01:08:53.540
[Amit Varma]: One is a punishment and the other is a probability of getting punished.

01:08:53.540 --> 01:09:00.540
[Amit Varma]: Now, as far as the quantum of punishment is concerned, India is not really much worse than most other developed countries.

01:09:00.540 --> 01:09:03.540
[Amit Varma]: And that's absolutely fine. We don't need to do anything there.

01:09:03.540 --> 01:09:10.540
[Amit Varma]: The problem there is a probability of getting punished, which is very low on three different margins.

01:09:10.540 --> 01:09:13.540
[Amit Varma]: The second is reporting rates are extremely low.

01:09:13.540 --> 01:09:16.540
[Amit Varma]: And the only thing that can solve this is higher state capacity.

01:09:16.540 --> 01:09:21.540
[Amit Varma]: Like you pointed out, India has about 130 policemen per 100,000 people.

01:09:21.540 --> 01:09:25.540
[Amit Varma]: This is much less than half of, say, the USA, which is more than 300.

01:09:25.540 --> 01:09:31.540
[Amit Varma]: We need to increase state capacity. What this would also do is that this would allow division of labor.

01:09:31.540 --> 01:09:38.540
[Amit Varma]: And within each police station, even if policemen remain largely misogynist, therefore reflecting our culture itself,

01:09:38.540 --> 01:09:47.540
[Amit Varma]: you can still have women's cells within each police station where women might feel more comfortable to go and to be able to report.

01:09:47.540 --> 01:09:49.540
[Amit Varma]: And they might even be better trained.

01:09:49.540 --> 01:09:58.540
[Amit Varma]: The second margin besides the reporting, the second area is the trial, where you pointed out that cases can drag on for 10 years or more.

01:09:58.540 --> 01:10:07.540
[Amit Varma]: And the only way around this, again, is expanding state capacity, having more judges who can act faster.

01:10:07.540 --> 01:10:12.540
[Amit Varma]: Again, we did have an episode on this, and that will be linked on the episode page of this.

01:10:12.540 --> 01:10:15.540
[Amit Varma]: A very deep problem, same kind of solution.

01:10:15.540 --> 01:10:20.540
[Amit Varma]: And the third is the conviction rates are very low, which is partly because cases drag on for so long.

01:10:20.540 --> 01:10:27.540
[Amit Varma]: It's partly because the police, of which there are so few, are already so overworked that they don't go through the proper procedures.

01:10:27.540 --> 01:10:29.540
[Amit Varma]: They're not trained to go through the procedures.

01:10:29.540 --> 01:10:31.540
[Amit Varma]: Evidence is often not taken.

01:10:31.540 --> 01:10:36.540
[Amit Varma]: And when it is taken, it's just lost or it degrades over time in different ways.

01:10:36.540 --> 01:10:44.540
[Amit Varma]: You know, the common solution to this entire mess would seem to be just increased state capacity as long as the rule of law is concerned.

01:10:44.540 --> 01:10:50.540
[Amit Varma]: But like you pointed out, that requires political will and the incentives for that are not good either.

01:10:50.540 --> 01:10:57.540
[Guest]: Yes, so having painted this terribly dismal picture, I do have some glimmers of hope, right?

01:10:57.540 --> 01:11:05.540
[Guest]: Now, you and I have had this conversation many times before that whenever the state has weak capacity and hasn't provided the public goods we need,

01:11:05.540 --> 01:11:07.540
[Guest]: the private sector steps in.

01:11:07.540 --> 01:11:11.540
[Guest]: Now, criminal justice is one of the areas where that's very difficult.

01:11:11.540 --> 01:11:14.540
[Guest]: Private sector can't easily step in.

01:11:14.540 --> 01:11:17.540
[Guest]: But there are margins on which it can.

01:11:17.540 --> 01:11:22.540
[Guest]: If you observe now, so many places have security cameras.

01:11:22.540 --> 01:11:30.540
[Guest]: The probability of getting caught privately by the security officer of the building or the mall or the workplace is much higher.

01:11:30.540 --> 01:11:33.540
[Guest]: That is a big deterrent to crime.

01:11:33.540 --> 01:11:36.540
[Guest]: Just the fact that there are video cameras everywhere at the workplace.

01:11:36.540 --> 01:11:42.540
[Guest]: So I know that is again a privilege of the rich people who work in the formal sector.

01:11:42.540 --> 01:11:45.540
[Guest]: But it's a really good start, right?

01:11:45.540 --> 01:11:57.540
[Guest]: The second is now post Vishakha, every firm in the formal sector was supposed to create a procedure and a committee to deal with sexual harassment and sexual assault.

01:11:57.540 --> 01:12:06.540
[Guest]: Now, the good thing about these committees is the standards for fair procedure are much lower than the criminal trial.

01:12:06.540 --> 01:12:12.540
[Guest]: And I say that that's a good thing because I don't want the state to relax the standards.

01:12:12.540 --> 01:12:18.540
[Guest]: I think it's a terrible idea to create fast track courts that compromise due process and things like that.

01:12:18.540 --> 01:12:25.540
[Guest]: But the state has a particular kind of monopoly over violence and that we want to keep these checks and balances on the state.

01:12:25.540 --> 01:12:30.540
[Guest]: But I am much less worried if there is a false positive at a workplace.

01:12:30.540 --> 01:12:31.540
[Guest]: Right.

01:12:31.540 --> 01:12:34.540
[Guest]: It's a he said, she said, and they believed her.

01:12:34.540 --> 01:12:37.540
[Guest]: And there's a false positive and someone was wrongfully accused.

01:12:37.540 --> 01:12:38.540
[Guest]: Fair enough.

01:12:38.540 --> 01:12:44.540
[Guest]: I think it's a terrible thing, but it is not as terrible as when state courts do it.

01:12:44.540 --> 01:12:45.540
[Amit Varma]: It's not seven years.

01:12:45.540 --> 01:12:46.540
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:12:46.540 --> 01:12:50.540
[Guest]: Which means I am a little bit more comfortable on the margin.

01:12:50.540 --> 01:12:51.540
[Guest]: Right.

01:12:51.540 --> 01:13:00.540
[Guest]: With relaxing those standards and second, I'm a little bit more optimistic about the results of that kind of procedure.

01:13:00.540 --> 01:13:02.540
[Guest]: Now, what's the consequence?

01:13:02.540 --> 01:13:03.540
[Guest]: You get fired.

01:13:03.540 --> 01:13:04.540
[Guest]: Right.

01:13:04.540 --> 01:13:05.540
[Guest]: And you lose reputation.

01:13:05.540 --> 01:13:07.540
[Guest]: And that's a terrible thing if you're an innocent person.

01:13:07.540 --> 01:13:12.540
[Guest]: And while it's a terrible thing, if you're an innocent person, it is still not as terrible as going to prison.

01:13:12.540 --> 01:13:33.540
[Guest]: But it's a wonderful thing if you're a woman in a workplace with not much power within the power structure of society and don't have the emotional, financial or political connections to go through the entire criminal justice system process for 10, 12, 15 years to get a conviction.

01:13:33.540 --> 01:13:45.540
[Guest]: So I think swift delivery of justice, even if there are some false positives, I'm comfortable with as long as these are decentralized versions of the procedure.

01:13:45.540 --> 01:13:46.540
[Guest]: Right.

01:13:46.540 --> 01:13:50.540
[Guest]: Not at the government level, but at the workplace level, at the association level.

01:13:50.540 --> 01:13:52.540
[Guest]: And again, there will be competition.

01:13:52.540 --> 01:13:53.540
[Guest]: Right.

01:13:52.540 --> 01:13:54.540
[Guest]: All of these things are trial and error process.

01:13:54.540 --> 01:14:03.540
[Guest]: If there are some people who have gone too much on the other side and there are too many false positives, men will think twice before they work at such a place.

01:14:03.540 --> 01:14:11.540
[Guest]: So what I mean is that I think this decentralized system is much quicker because of the trial and error process.

01:14:11.540 --> 01:14:15.540
[Guest]: And second, the justice is swift.

01:14:15.540 --> 01:14:18.540
[Guest]: The consequences are immediate and sometimes can also be long term.

01:14:18.540 --> 01:14:20.540
[Guest]: There are real economic consequences.

01:14:20.540 --> 01:14:27.540
[Guest]: And I think that is the answer to this very dismal picture that I paint at the state level.

01:14:27.540 --> 01:14:32.540
[Guest]: The problem with that answer is most of India works in the informal sector.

01:14:32.540 --> 01:14:42.540
[Guest]: And we've got to fix that and bring more of India's informal sector into the light so that all women can have this protection of an internal committee process.

01:14:42.540 --> 01:14:43.540
[Amit Varma]: I agree with that.

01:14:43.540 --> 01:14:55.540
[Amit Varma]: And beyond just a workplace context, if I might segue back to MeToo for a moment, what you've seen in MeToo over the last, you know, since it broke, is that none of these people have yet been legally punished.

01:14:55.540 --> 01:14:57.540
[Amit Varma]: The legal system hasn't even come into play.

01:14:57.540 --> 01:15:03.540
[Amit Varma]: What is instead happening is that social sanctions have become swifter and more severe.

01:15:03.540 --> 01:15:04.540
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:15:04.540 --> 01:15:05.540
[Amit Varma]: A lot of people have been sacked.

01:15:05.540 --> 01:15:09.540
[Amit Varma]: A lot of people have had their careers ruined and thank goodness for that.

01:15:09.540 --> 01:15:20.540
[Amit Varma]: And the way I saw a lot of it play out, the MeToo movement, and it's very fascinating to me as someone who's thought about the subject of spontaneous order, is that this is spontaneous order in action.

01:15:20.540 --> 01:15:24.540
[Amit Varma]: The MeToo movement wasn't centrally planned from anywhere.

01:15:24.540 --> 01:15:29.540
[Amit Varma]: It kind of arose organically and there were, you know, different kinds of ebbs and flows.

01:15:29.540 --> 01:15:34.540
[Amit Varma]: And within the movement, you had different people who gained credibility over a period of time.

01:15:34.540 --> 01:15:44.540
[Amit Varma]: And it's still playing out, you know, in real time, which is really fascinating and maybe a subject for us to talk about or write about at a different point in time.

01:15:44.540 --> 01:15:46.540
[Amit Varma]: I think I've taken a lot of your time today, Shruti.

01:15:46.540 --> 01:15:57.540
[Amit Varma]: So before I sign off, you know, any final words on the lessons of criminal economics for the state of women in India?

01:15:57.540 --> 01:16:11.540
[Guest]: I think the lessons are we need to impose a higher cost, a higher expected cost, which means we either improve the probability that the cost will be faced for the actual cost.

01:16:11.540 --> 01:16:21.540
[Guest]: The probability can be increased either by social shaming and shunning, reporting on social media, MeToo movement, or actually making the criminal justice system better.

01:16:21.540 --> 01:16:24.540
[Guest]: These are all available options for reform.

01:16:24.540 --> 01:16:32.540
[Guest]: And the social cost can be improved by both legal mechanisms in terms of what is the actual punishment for sexual assault,

01:16:32.540 --> 01:16:41.540
[Guest]: but also what is the social punishment for sexual assault, which is getting dropped from projects and losing your job and losing association membership and so on and so forth.

01:16:41.540 --> 01:16:45.540
[Guest]: So I think there is much to do on both these sides.

01:16:45.540 --> 01:16:55.540
[Guest]: The wonderful thing is this has started happening, but I think the MeToo movement, really, all of us need to be in it for the long haul, right?

01:16:55.540 --> 01:17:02.540
[Guest]: This can't be just a cultural moment where we are fascinated by everything that's happening every single day.

01:17:02.540 --> 01:17:09.540
[Guest]: And we're all in shock and awe that these predators existed in plain sight or that it's all like cracking open right now.

01:17:09.540 --> 01:17:11.540
[Guest]: That's sort of what's happening right now.

01:17:11.540 --> 01:17:17.540
[Guest]: The big thing we need is every firm, every building, every school, every temple trust,

01:17:17.540 --> 01:17:26.540
[Guest]: everybody needs to create some internal procedures so that we can actually prevent this in the future, right?

01:17:26.540 --> 01:17:32.540
[Guest]: The sad part of the MeToo movement is that there are this many victims and we are still at the tip of the iceberg.

01:17:32.540 --> 01:17:46.540
[Guest]: So in the future, we've got to stop having so many victims and that is possible only if we change the incentives, both in terms of probability of facing some kind of sanction and the actual sanctions.

01:17:46.540 --> 01:17:50.540
[Amit Varma]: Shruti, that's a great note to end on. Thanks so much for your time.

01:17:50.540 --> 01:17:52.540
